title: For Sale:  H&R Young America 22 Rimfire
postcontent:
I had a seller for this however after the 3rd day of him failing to set up a meet like he said I decided to forget his deal. Now if you previously emailed me about this feel free to do it again as I thought it was sold.

Here I have a very nice H&R Young America Kids 22 Rimfire Pistol. Now the Young America series spanned from a black powder version in the 1890’s into the last version of 1942. Unfortunately H&R has a bad track record of keeping exact production date lists for serial numbers as it was not a high priority. There is generally considered to be two main versions and the 1st one is the black powder version. Now there is the 2nd version which was the modern smokeless powder cartridges, however there is a few sub versions in the 2nd version. There is a few key differences in the 2nd version and the 1st the name itself as the original name was the Young America as later in the production life of the revolver it changed slightly to Young American which they just added the N to the end of the name. Then there is the fact that this one is Blued as the majority of them were Nickel finish and it is estimated that less than 5% were Blued which causes a Blued version to bring a minimum premium of 15% or more over the normal value. As seen the condition of my Young America is very good! I am including 3 photos of this beauty but have many more so email me for more. I was offered $200 from the owner of a local gun shop. So I figure I will start at $250 and see what I can get. I realize that H&R is not generally considered collectible but there is a few H&R firearms that are collectible like this kids pistol that dates from somewhere in the 1920’s to 1930’s. You can see that this is tiny by the $20 used to scale the size, this is truly unique. Also this is chambered in 22 Short, it says 22 Rimfire but will not chamber 22LR but could possibly chamber 22 Long. I have fired this many times and it shoots good considering it’s such a small revolver, I have personally fired 150 rds of 22 Short through this pistol. As I sated, this shoots quite well but with its small size and my large hands it can be a little uncomfortable but then again it is designed for a child’s hand.

Caliber:  .44 with 20 gauge lower barrel

Search 'The Museum of the Confederacy Tribute Revolver' for offical pics and detail.

The Museum of the Confederacy Tribute Revolver combines the classic design of the fabled LeMat revolver with striking 24-karat gold and nickel artwork honoring the legacy of the Confederate soldiers and their leaders who valiantly fought for the cause of the Confederacy.

The LeMat's unique nine-shot cylinder holds the portraits of three of the Confederacy's favorite sons. Right side features revered Confederate General Robert E. Lee, and the left side features the gallant Cavalry Major General J.E.B. Stuart. 

Both are surrounded by flowing scrollwork and crossed rifles of the Confederate Infantry. Jefferson Davis, President of the Confederate States of America, is featured on top of the cylinder.

The frame of the Tribute is adorned on both sides with a Confederate flag displayed within a field of scrollwork. The "CS", or Confederate States, belt buckle is featured on the breech of the barrel. The official seal of the Museum of the Confederacy is also featured on the smoothbore shotgun barrel, surrounded by matching scrollwork.

Along the right side of the barrel, the issue is identified as "The Museum of the Confederacy Tribute" in a classic banner tipped in matching scrollwork. Each Tribute's individual edition number is featured on top of the barrel near the sight.
